[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Considering Java class structures**\n\nI’m thinking about Java's rule that allows only one public top-level class per file. I wonder if using nested public static classes inside a public test class helps with this. The public methods of these nested classes should be accessible, right? It's interesting that binary names have a dollar sign ($), while source class names don’t. Maybe I could separate helpers into different public files to avoid issues with names. This seems like a better option!\n\n**Clarifying file structure**\n\nI need to maintain a one-to-one mapping between dynamic-access report classes and generated test class files. It seems that extra Java files might break things. Each dynamic-access report class should ideally be in its own dedicated Java test file, but the rule doesn’t explicitly forbid helper source files. Still, the one-to-one mapping suggests I shouldn’t create multiple test files. So, I’ll keep them nested and plan a patch to address this.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0b267c8e10b533b3016a42496319e08194a67fba306a181471\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqQklwBvAAP6knXYIge5hNkC1Cw6an4rk0wiwuCdh-nL-Nq40gvyHCTsqLGIEqSlH-6EehggHod9lk3Q63wROeZun0Hy3gb9fEAXBc8ojob6cqf4HiLP0byc5gj1_A1beFMow_2enlLmyaWGLxqcHimwKciAXYEi75Syiihglv_0GRdadN6bMReWXkN83yjjtxyonoG5SpNA79wmRT0w0TeQ4rH8C1Yl1AvUvnHvucFe6LMfG8KzVh5w80vZ2Lvn1xb5qaz4znho54vZt2g7CO0R7uvBSnK2jMOywPz_nOegRWgQYnFEzwJBqha-L3cV5HDL2b_cfSN2c5HWtxgX4sj_QtI2C9k32OYhTMHHK6_L19rMSEAjVrS6fwwttAZ99_ku57x-AFo0qEo-4BjqCQ3qVq996QUML0lySltWdY89c35blf3hVZ2t-1RzcgANQx2DrssSAHPKRvbUcwGqibMkyAudBwNVHpU29f6cNdvGGEH1DXYC5q_ykHS7Qe023iw5HmYIVHS3CZHUT8oWle_9sPJ512BuzKLtMXZAehKiZAlfUvPFL--A68_x22cASRSeS60NUtJc8rflKDFbgTKsSiUGZWhJ2aY7UG9kLvWgEXRpXPnxEi2LpS0OB3WlloPJxxkAfENQ4QqKzE-yQFNwq8JTkfAJ9FOKUkGtgObUZFakdAuFJvMaGLZRm8R7vEXGB1B9Y1Y5ek-YNGt9NteNwDkUSmpmLpnCokuX2kCu